commit.message:
configure.ac: fix the version numbering scheme.

I had the version as 0.6.0 in configure.ac, when it should have been
0.0.6. This only became apparent as I was finalizing the release.
Oops. Let's call it 0.0.7 now.

NEWS: move my release announcement to the top.

This way it's clear that the v0.0.6 release includes the new keyboard
and fullscreen support.
Makefile.am: include HISTORY and README.md in the release tarball.

src/hdaps-gl.c: cosmetic change to "case" statement.

There's no need to "break" out of the case statement after calling
exit(), since exit() doesn't return. The "break" was omitted from
the previous case (handling the 'q' key), so let's omit it from the
"Esc" case as well.

README.md: combine autoreconf/autoconf commands into "autoreconf -fi".

Running autoreconf should take care of everything for you, if you pass
it the --force flag to keep it from thinking.
NEWS: add a file for news, like when we fork the project to GitHub.

HISTORY: move project history into a separate file.

Instead of including the project history in a comment at the top of
src/hdaps-gl.c, I have moved it out into its own file called HISTORY.
This makes room at the top of hdaps-gl.c to include the GPL-2 (only)
header suggested by the FSF and GNU, which is now included.

Moreover, I have added an AUTHORS file containing the names of the
three people that I am certain have copyright claims to the code,
whole tales were told in commit e781be1e while adding the COPYING
file.

COPYING: add GPL-2 license.

This one has a bit of history. From the comments at the top of
hdaps-gl.c, it looks like that C file was born as an OpenGL tutorial
that was written by Jeff Molofee,

  https://nehe.gamedev.net/tutorial/lessons_01__05/22004/

and then ported to Linux/GLUT by Richard Campbell. These are tutorials
that just show you how to use a public API.

The next name mentioned in that comment is Jesper Juhl, whose part in
its development is unclear. I can find no mention of the file
ibm_hdaps_userspace.c on the internet.

Finally, both Patrick "Petschge" Kilian (petschge@web.de) and Robert
Love (rml@novell.com) have agreed to license the code as GPL-2, with
no "or later" clause:

  * https://sourceforge.net/p/hdaps/mailman/message/3017854/
  * https://sourceforge.net/p/hdaps/mailman/message/3017897/

In an effort to clarify the issue, I have attempted to contact...

  * Jeff Molofee (support@nehe.me),
  * Richard Campbell (ulmont@bellsouth.net), and
  * Jesper Juhl (jj@chaosbits.net, jesper.juhl@gmail.com,
                 juhl-lkml@dif.dk, jesperjuhl76@gmail.com).

The message to Jeff Molofee timed out after a week. Richard Campbell's
address came back undeliverable (addressee unknown) immediately. One
of Jesper Juhl's addresses was deliverable, but I have received no
response after a week. This all leaves me back where I started, making
a judgment call, based on two factors:

  * Jeff Molofee and Richard Campbell's contribution was to demonstrate
    how to use a public API, and in small enough portions, I don't feel
    that this is copyrightable.

  * In the first mailing list message above, Robert Love says that he
    rewrote most of the code, and that the bulk of it is Patrick's
    laptop graphic.

Since both Robert and Patrick have agreed to GPL-2, I think the work
as a whole is GPL-2.

Print a better error message when position file is missing.

If your HDAPS kernel module isn't loaded, hdaps-gl will spit out

  open: No such file or directory

which doesn't help too much. Instead, we now check for ENOENT on that
open() call, and print out

  File /sys/devices/platform/hdaps/position not found. Is the HDAPS kernel
  module loaded?

Moreover, if some other error occurs during open(), we'll print the
path that it happened with. For example,

  open (/sys/devices/platform/hdaps/position): Input/output error
configure.ac: comment which packages contain the headers we need.

autotools: add (functional!) skeleton build system.

Create the basic files needed for an autotools build system:

  * A configure.ac file that checks for the headers and libraries
    that we use. I've made myself the bug-reports address for now.

  * A top-level Makefile.am that just points to the src/ directory.

  * An src/Makefile.am that basically just contains the name of the
    executable we're going to build.

autotools: remove the handwritten Makefile, and move the source to src/.

This is in preparation for an autotools build system. The Makefile
will ultimately be generated by a ./configure script, and the fact
that autotools likes to drop junk into the top-level directory makes
it a bit nicer to keep the program sources in src/.
Initial commit: upstream v0.0.5 from SourceForge.
